{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489391","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489391"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:15:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:15:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"648"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/648"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.39,0.03,0.29,0.2,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"648"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55331"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"648","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/648"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"648"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40859"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1046"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2756"},{"type":"tags","id":"4959"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"12912"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2018"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2677"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12277"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44922"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55331"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of recurrent brisk right-sided nose bleeding, with each episode lasting for up to one hour and requiring nasal packing. He sustained an injury to his nose three days ago and has not had any previous history of nasal bleeding. He has a medical history of asthma. His medications include salbutamol inhaler as needed. He does not take any anticoagulants or antiplatelet medications. He is a non-smoker and drinks four to five alcoholic drinks each week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 70/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. He has no other bruises or contusions noted on his body. Currently, he is using a nasal pack to control the bleeding and he is on prophylactic antibiotics. His current nasal pack has been in place overnight. Investigations reveal an INR of 1.0 (0.9-1.2), platelets 311 x 10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (150-450), haemoglobin 140 g/L (135-180), and all other haematological tests are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Keep nasal pack until bleeding stops and then cauterise Little\u0027s area","Admit and arrange to remove the nasal pack the following day","Admit for nasal rhinoscopy and possible surgical intervention","Remove nasal pack and cauterise Little\u0027s area","Keep nasal pack until bleeding stops and then discharge"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with recurrent epistaxis following nasal trauma that has not responded to nasal packing. Given the persistent nature of the bleeding and its unresponsiveness to conservative measures, the most appropriate next step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eadmit for nasal rhinoscopy and possible surgical intervention\u003C/strong\u003E. Nasal rhinoscopy allows for direct visualisation of the bleeding source and enables targeted treatment, which may include cauterisation of the bleeding vessel or, if necessary, surgical intervention such as arterial ligation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeeping the nasal pack until bleeding stops and then cauterising Little\u0027s area\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this case. Blind cauterisation of Little\u0027s area without first identifying the source of bleeding through rhinoscopy could miss the actual bleeding site, especially given the history of trauma and the possibility of a more posterior source of bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmitting and arranging to remove the nasal pack the following day\u003C/strong\u003E is not the best course of action. This approach does not address the underlying cause of the persistent bleeding and is likely to result in continued epistaxis once the pack is removed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemoving the nasal pack and cauterising Little\u0027s area\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended without first performing rhinoscopy to identify the source of bleeding. Blind cauterisation could be ineffective or potentially harmful if the bleeding source is not in Little\u0027s area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKeeping the nasal pack until bleeding stops and then discharging\u003C/strong\u003E the patient is not appropriate given the recurrent nature of the bleeding and its failure to respond to packing alone. This approach risks further episodes of epistaxis after discharge without addressing the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn cases of recurrent epistaxis following trauma, especially when unresponsive to conservative measures, it\u0027s important to consider the possibility of an anterior ethmoid artery bleed. This type of bleeding often requires surgical intervention, such as arterial ligation, which further supports the need for admission, rhinoscopy, and possible surgical management. The priority is to identify and definitively treat the source of bleeding to prevent further recurrences and potential complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["In patients with persistent nasal bleeding that is unresponsive to packing, nasal rhinoscopy is required to evaluate the source of bleeding and treat appropriately.","Recurrent epistaxis following trauma may indicate an anterior ethmoid artery bleed, which may require surgical ligation.","Blind cauterisation of Little\u0027s area is not appropriate for persistent epistaxis unresponsive to nasal packing."],"references":["Tunkel DE, Anne S, Payne SC, Ishman SL, Rosenfeld RM, Abramson PJ, et al. Clinical Practice Guideline: Nosebleed (Epistaxis). Otolaryngol Head Neck Surg. 2020;162(1):S1-S38. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/31910111/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40859"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"648"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40859"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-14T19:57:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-14T19:59:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"648"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55331"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"c